Individual brain cells were up and running, performing their basic duties of taking up oxygen and producing carbon dioxide.
“The conventional wisdom is brain cells die, irretrievably, after about 10 to 12 minutes without oxygen — and that’s part of the scientific underpinning for the definition of brain death, the definition of death in humans.
The goal was to test if individual brain cells could be revived in this manner.
After six hours on the BrainEx — 10 hours after slaughter — the researchers didn’t see signs of consciousness in the brains.
What Sestan and his team are claiming is they kept the individual cells of the brain alive, hours after the pig was killed.